  "prompt": "How do you compare transduction, transformation, and conjugation?",
  "response": "Here's a comparison of transduction, transformation, and conjugation:\n\nTransduction:\n- DNA transfer mediated by bacteriophages (viruses)\n- Involves viral particles as transfer vehicles\n- DNA is packaged inside viral particles\n- Occurs primarily in bacteria\n- Relatively random gene transfer\n- Can transfer larger DNA segments\n- Requires viral intermediary\n\nTransformation:\n- Direct uptake of naked DNA from environment\n- No living transfer agent involved\n- DNA directly enters bacterial cell\n- Requires specific competence conditions\n- Limited DNA transfer amount\n- More common in laboratory settings\n- Relies on cell's ability to absorb external DNA\n\nConjugation:\n- Direct cell-to-cell DNA transfer\n- Requires physical contact between donor and recipient cells\n- Uses specialized bacterial structure (pilus)\n- Transfers plasmid DNA\n- More controlled gene transfer\n- One-way transfer process\n- Typically occurs between closely related bacteria\n- Involves specific genetic machinery\n\nKey similarities:\n- All mechanisms of horizontal gene transfer\n- Occur in bacterial populations\n- Can contribute to genetic diversity\n- Potential for spreading antibiotic resistance\n\nKey differences:\n- Transfer mechanism\n- DNA transfer efficiency\n- Genetic material transferred\n- Cellular requirements\n\nEach mechanism plays a unique role in bacterial genetic exchange and evolution.",
